questions.explanation:
Idempotency targets **duplicates**, not loss. Loss is handled by retries (at-least-once); duplicates are handled by making the operation safe to repeat — or by remembering an idempotency key and ignoring repeats:

```js
const seen = new Set(), log = [];
const handle = (id) => seen.has(id) ? log.push(id + ":dup") : (seen.add(id), log.push(id + ":ok"));
handle("m1"); handle("m1");
console.log(log); // ["m1:ok", "m1:dup"]  ← second one is a no-op
```

This is exactly Stripe's `Idempotency-Key` pattern: retrying a charge with the same key never double-charges. The false option mixes up the two concerns — an idempotent handler still needs at-least-once delivery underneath so that genuinely lost messages get retried at all.
